\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Segregation of subhalos is a phenomenon where subhalos with particular propertie
s (such as mass at accretion) exhibit different radial profiles in their
 host halos.
 For example, subhalos with larger maximum circular velocity (i.e., having
 deeper potential depth) tend to be closer to the center of their host halos
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wu_etal2013"

\end_inset

, while some studies found that more massive subhalos are less centrally
 concentrated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "angulo_09,contini_11,de_lucia_04,reed05"

\end_inset

.
 In terms of dynamical friction, more massive subhalos (or the ones with
 larger maximum circular velocities) are expected to be closer to the center;
 however, they experience more tidal mass loss due to stronger tidal fields.
 It is hard to decouple those two competing effects, and this is why several
 studies find an opposite trend in the radial distributions.
 There are several studies showing that subhalos selected based on their
 masses at accretion and at present show different radial distributions;
 subhalos selected by their masses at accretion show more centrally concentrated
 radial profiles than the ones selected by their present-day masses (e.g.,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nagai05"

\end_inset

).
 Characterizing segregation is sensitive to the selection of the subhalos
 and their chosen properties.
 Ref.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 investigated the segregation of dark matter subhalos in great details using
 Spearman rank-order correlations to quantitatively evaluate the correlation
 between 12 different subhalo properties and segregation indicators (such
 as orbital energy and halo-centric radius).
 Ref.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 found that accretion redshifts, which are the redshifts that subhalos are
 accreted by their host halos, is one of the major segregation property;
 subhalos accreted earlier tend to have more centrally concentrated radial
 distributions than the ones accreted later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is crucial to understand how a particular choice of subhalos cluster
 differently on small scales; different radial profiles will change 1-halo
 terms in correlation functions as well as 
\color black
small-scale redshift-space distortions.
 Those can possibly cause systematic errors/biases on large scale measurements
\color inherit
 [
\color red
zentner,hearin_15
\color inherit
].
 In this chapter, we first investigate whether segregation of subhalos on
 radial profiles depends on their host halo masses.
 Then, we compute its observational signature using two-point correlation
 functions.
 Understanding segregation of the subhalos and comparing that to segregation
 of galaxies will provide the clues for the connection between halos and
 galaxies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[connection/bridge]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assembly history of host halos is essential to the clustering known
 as an assembly bias, which is a phenomenon that the clustering of halos
 exhibits a dependence on additional properties beyond their mass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gao_etal05,wechsler06,gao_white07,li_etal08,hahn_etal09"

\end_inset

.
 In terms of the peak-background split formalism (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sheth_tormen99"

\end_inset

), the peaks of the same height in the initial density fluctuation collapse
 into the halos of the same mass; those peaks can be in different environments
 (i.e., some peaks are in over-dense regions while the others are in under-dense
 regions) and therefore have different assembly histories and clustering
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dalal_etal08"

\end_inset

.
 This environmental differences results in the differences in the structural
 properties/internal structure of halos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bullock01,wechsler02,hahn_etal07b,faltenbacher_white10"

\end_inset

.
 We revisit the manifestation of assembly history on the internal structure
 of the host halos regarding to segregation.
 In particular, we explore whether segregation of the subhalos in their
 radial distributions shows some dependence on internal properties of host
 halos such as concentration, which has strong correlation with their assembly
 history.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outline of this paper is as follows.
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 summarizes the simulations we use in this work.
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3 presents our primary results - mass dependence of segregation on radial
 profiles, its observational signature, and effects of assembly bias on
 segregation.
 We conclude in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the Bolshoi simulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bolshoi_11"

\end_inset

 which was run with the Adaptive Refinement Tree Code 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov_etal97,gottloeber_klypin08"

\end_inset

 assuming a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model with cosmological parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.27$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.73$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}=0.0469$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.82$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.70$
\end_inset

.
 The Bolshoi simulation used 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $250h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 box with a force resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

, giving a particle mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.35\times10^{8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos and subhalos are identified using the 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 phase-space, temporal halo finder 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar"

\end_inset

 and merger trees are constructed using the 
\family typewriter
CONSISTENT TREES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar_trees"

\end_inset


\family default
  procedures
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The catalogues used in this paper are publicly available at 
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://hipacc.ucsc.edu/Bolshoi/MergerTrees.html
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The results we consider in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:correlation_fn"

\end_inset

 use the output of the simulation at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows, we use the virial masses and maximum circular velocities
 (tagged 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
mvir
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
vmax
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) directly from the halo catalogues.
 The 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 halo finder computes halo masses based on spherical overdensities using
 a threshold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}=360$
\end_inset

.
 The halo mass and velocity functions start to show incompleteness at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim200$
\end_inset

 particles) for the Bolshoi simulation.
 Below those masses, the halo mass distributions show unphysical drop-offs
 indicating incomplete mass resolution.
 Therefore, we only select subhalos whose masses at accretion are greater
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mass Dependence of Segregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the mass dependence of segregation by comparing
 the radial distribution of subhalos with different host halo masses.
 We select host halos in three mass bins: 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, for each sample, we split their corresponding subhalos based on the
 accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $<0.1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1-0.25$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.25-0.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 We chose 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0.25$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

 to split samples, because the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

 reach their first peri-center at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, while subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.25$
\end_inset

 move to their first apo-centric passage according to Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 (see Fig.7).
 We also split samples at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

, because the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

 complete their first 
\color red
orbiting
\color inherit
 and move back to the center.
 So, the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 are the ones which orbit inside their host halos several times.
 Using those subsamples, we compute the radial distances normalized by their
 virial radius.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_massDependence"

\end_inset

 shows present radial profiles of subhalos as a function of the accretion
 redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 The solid lines are for the subhalos in the host halos whose masses are
 greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, while circles and dashed lines correspond to the host halos whose masses
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 For the samples with the same accretion redshifts 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

, the radial profiles of the subhalos with different host halo masses do
 not exhibit any significant differences, which implies that segregation
 of subhalos is independent of host halo mass.
 Radial profiles with different accretion redshifts 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 tell us how subhalos move inside their host halos after accretion; most
 of subhalos accreted after 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.1$
\end_inset

 are still close to the virial radius of their host halos, while the ones
 accreted around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.1-0.25$
\end_inset

 move towards center.
 After going through their first peri-center, the subhalos move back to
 their apo-centric passage, and this is why the subhalos accreted around
 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.1-0.25$
\end_inset

 show more centrally concentrated radial profiles than the ones accreted
 around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.25-0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The subhalos which are accreted earlier (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

) are closer to the center due to the inside-out assembly of dark matter
 halos (i.e., the virial radius of their host halos were smaller when those
 subhalos were accreted).
 This result is consistent with Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 (see Fig.
 7).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/radialDist_z_acc_massDependence.pdf
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:radial_massDependence"

\end_inset

Radial profiles of subhalos as a function of the accretion redshifts 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 The solid lines are for the subhalos in the host halos whose masses are
 greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, while circles and dashed lines correspond to the host halos whose masses
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}-10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The blue lines correspond to the subhalos which are accreted after 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.1$
\end_inset

, the green lines are for the ones which are accreted around 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1-0.25$
\end_inset

, the red lines are the ones accreted around 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.25,-0.5$
\end_inset

, and the cyan lines are the ones accreted before 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 According to Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

, the subhalos accreted at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

 reach their first peri-center and the ones accreted at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.25$
\end_inset

 are at their first peri-centric passage at present.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We further explore how subhalos move after accretion by computing the average
 halo-centric radius as a function of the accretion redshift as shown in
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

.
 We first rank-order the subhalos based on their accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and split them in 30 equal number bins.
 Then, we compute the average halo-centric radius for each bin.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

 clearly shows the characteristic of an orbit and does not show any mass-depende
nt feature for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

, their average halo-centric radius show little indication of an orbit.
 This is probably due to major mergers and violent relaxation afterwards.
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

 predicted the halo-centric radius based on the adiabatic model; however,
 the prediction gave a smaller halo-centric radius for more massive host
 halos, while Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

 shows a weak but an opposite trend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots_Cluster/subhalo_z_acc_mean.pdf
	width 70text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

The average halo-centric radius 
\begin_inset Formula $<r/R_{{\rm vir}}>$
\end_inset

 as a function of the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 for the host halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 (blue), 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13.5}-10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 (green), and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{13}-10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 The blue dashed lines correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.25$
\end_inset

.
 All those lines show the almost same average halo-centric radii; however,
 for subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

, subhalos in larger host halos have slightly larger halo-centric radii
 than the ones in smaller halos.
 The difference between blue and red lines are about 0.5.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the accretion redshift we use is the redshift that the subhalo
 is accreted most recently, but not all the subhalos stay inside of their
 host halos after accretion.
 There are some subhalos which move out from their host halos.
 Those halos are called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ejected halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and treating them as host halos or subhalos alter the clustering on small
 scales (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13,sunayama16"

\end_inset

).
 Even though those ejected halos are outside of the virial radius, they
 are likely to be gravitationally bound and are accreted again.
 Some of the subhalos in the samples follow that scenario.
 So, we use the first accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

, which is the redshift that the subhalo is accreted first time, and repeat
 the same analysis done for Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_massDependence"

\end_inset

 and Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

.
 Here, we use the subhalos whose host halo masses are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, but the same result holds for the subhalos with different host halo masses.
 The left panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:z_first"

\end_inset

 compares the average halo-centric radius as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

.
 They do not show any significant differences up to 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.4$
\end_inset

, while the average radius based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

 is almost 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 larger than the one for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.4$
\end_inset

.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.4$
\end_inset

, we preferentially select subhalos which are more tightly bound to their
 host halos (because they never move out after accretion) and this is why
 the average radius is smaller for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 The right panel shows radial profiles of subhalos for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 By using the first accretion redshift, the radial distribution becomes
 less concentrated.
\end_layout

