\begin_layout Subsection
Correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the correlation between the accretion redshift
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and the retained mass and maximum circular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the subhalo mass/maximum circular velocity at present (in this case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the subhalo mass/maximum circular velocity at accretion.
 The retained mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 measures the mass loss after subhalos are accreted by their host halos,
 and it is tightly correlated with the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 due to tidal stripping.
 As a general trend, subhalos which are accreted earlier experience more
 mass loss because they stay in their host halos longer.
 The question is how well this property 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 correlates with the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we use the subhalos in the host halos whose masses are greater
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:correlation"

\end_inset

 shows correlation of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 as well as with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,acc}}$
\end_inset

 are the maximum circular velocity at present time and at accretion.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are tightly correlated with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is expected, because the subhalos which are accreted earlier must
 be striped more mass due to tidal stripping.
 Quantitatively, the cross correlation coefficients for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is 0.651, while it is 0.403 for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
 As is clear from the figures, the change in halo mass is larger than the
 change in the maximum circular velocity.
 This is mostly because approximately the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}\propto M_{{\rm vir}}^{1/3}$
\end_inset

 holds.
 Applying this scaling relation and converting 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, the slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is almost the same as the slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.6$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/old_ts485/Desktop/my_thesis/plots_Cluster/scatter_z_massLoss2.pdf
	lyxscale 70
	width 50text%

\end_inset


