\begin_layout Standard

\color black
At last, we compare the subhalo velocity with respect to the velocity of
 their host halos for various 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hist_vel"

\end_inset

.
 The figure shows that the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.25$
\end_inset

 have larger internal velocities than the ones with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.25$
\end_inset

.
 Quantitatively, the median value for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.25$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1123.9$
\end_inset

km/s, while it is 
\begin_inset Formula $731.2$
\end_inset

km/s for the ones with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.25$
\end_inset

.
 
\color red
This is probably because the subhalos accreted earlier already lost their
 kinetic energy due to dynamical friction.

\color black
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:hist_vel"

\end_inset

 is consistent with Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:xi_mu"

\end_inset

 in the sense that small internal velocities for subhalo with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

 will make the amplitude of the redshift-space correlation functions at
 the most inner region larger, because the pair-distances for those subhalos
 will not be elongated as much as the ones for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

