\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of Assembly Bias on Segregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate whether the assembly history of the host
 halos affects the subhalo mass functions and spatial distribution of the
 subhalos.
 We first select the host halos whose masses are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, but the same result still holds for different host halo masses
\color black
.
 Then, we split them based on their concentration.
 
\color inherit
We use the median concentration-mass relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 shown in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dutton_maccio14"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\rm log}_{10}\bar{c}=-0.097{\rm log_{10}M_{vir}}+2.148.\label{eq:concen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For every halo in the Bolshoi catalogs, we use its tabulated 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}}),$
\end_inset

 and then use the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset

 to compare with the measured concentration for every halo.
 We will henceforth refer to halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $c<\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low-concentration halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $c>\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high-concentration halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 We use concentration as an indicator of assembly history: Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wechsler06"

\end_inset

 showed that early-forming halos tend to have higher concentration than
 late-forming halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the same samples of halos, we split subhalos based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and compare their radial distributions as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radialDist_concen"

\end_inset

.
 While the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

 do not exhibit any difference in the spatial distribution for the high/low-conc
entration host halos, the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 have similar inner distribution but different outer distributions.
 The subhalos in the high concentration host halos show steeper decrease
 as the distance gets closer to the virial radius.
 If the distribution of the early-accreted subhalos is virialized (
\color red
how could I phrase this correctly?
\color inherit
), it makes sense that there are more subhalos at outer radius in the low-concen
tration host halos, because they follow more like the NFW profile 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nfw97"

\end_inset

.
 The another way of explaining this phenomenon is that the high-concentration
 halos have a deeper potential depth and therefore their subhalos are more
 tightly bound to the core.
\end_layout

