\begin_layout Section
Discussions/Future Works
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we investigate environmental effects on segregation of subhalos
 using the accretion redshift.
 We first study whether the segregation on radial profiles show any dependences
 on the host halo mass.
 Then, we further explore whether assembly history of host halos affect
 the radial distributions.
 In addition to them, we also computed two-point correlation functions for
 samples of subhalos (split by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

) as its expected observational signature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude this chapter with the following summary of our findings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Segregation of subhalos on radial profiles is independent of host halo mass.
 Until subhalos complete their first 
\color red
orbiting
\color inherit
 (i..e, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

), they show clear characteristic of an orbit (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo_centric1"

\end_inset

).
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

, their average halo-centric radius is almost the same for any 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 (possibly) due to major mergers and the violent relaxation.
 Since the segregation is independent of the host halo mass, we can measure/comp
are this to galaxy segregation for clusters as well as groups.
 The generic trend is consistent with the findings in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vdBosch16"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.4$
\end_inset

, using 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

 give little difference on the radial distributions, while the average halo-cent
ric radius based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 larger than the one using 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.4$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of galaxy formation, galaxy property may be more correlated with
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

, and comparing our finding to observations can be a good test to tell which
 accretion redshift is more important for galaxy formation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 are correlated, we test how much of segregation actually comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 by generating samples with the same dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 For the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

, subhalos which lost more mass are preferentially closer to the center,
 while there is no correlation between the amount of mass loss and the radial
 distribution for the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We found that assembly history of host halos do not affect the radial distributi
on of subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 show weak dependence on the concentration of their host halos; the inner
 region does not show any difference, while the outer region shows some
 amplitude difference.
 [can be more quantitative?]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We found that the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

 have the almost twice large amplitude for the redshift-space correlation
 functions at the most inner region compared to that for the subhalos with
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 This is because the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}<0.5$
\end_inset

 have almost 
\begin_inset Formula $50\%$
\end_inset

 larger internal velocity (i.e., the subhalo velocity with respect to the
 velocity of its host halo) than the subhalos with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a possible direction for future works, we can compare segregation on
 radial profiles from simulations to observations using the age-matching
 technique, which connects the star formation rate of galaxies to the formation
 time of its dark matter halos (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hearin_etal13b"

\end_inset

).
 This will tell us whether galaxy property (such as color) is correlated
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc,first}}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, we can extend our analysis with assembly bias by using other parameters
 such as spin (which is a good indicator of recent mergers).
 In observations, some clusters/groups probably experience recent mergers.
 In order to compare the result from simulations to observations, it is
 good to know how merger changes the radial distribution of subhalos and
 affects the segregation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Appendix?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:subhaloMassFn"

\end_inset

 shows unevolved and evolved subhalo mass functions for high/low-concentration
 host halos.
 Note that the unevolved subhalo mass function implies that we use the subhalo
 mass at accretion, while we use the subhalo mass at present time for the
 evolved subhalo mass function.
 Both subhalo mass functions indicate that the subhalo mass functions for
 high-concentration halos have fewer subhalos for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm acc}}/M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{-1.5}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is the subhalo mass at accretion and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 is the host halo mass at present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-> I wanted to say that high-concentration halos tend to live in under-dense
 regions and therefore the amplitude of the subhalo mass function is smaller
 than the one for low-concentration halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

